[## [SECTION: Step 9 — Alembic Baseline Migration (Component #22)]]

17
01:06:36,000 --> 01:06:42,000
Now let's set up Alembic for database migrations.
Alembic is the official migration tool for SQLAlchemy.

18
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:48,000
In Phase one, we used Docker's init script to create the schema.
Now we establish Alembic as the official source of migration truth.

19
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:54,000
Why Alembic? Because as our application evolves,
we will need to add columns, create new tables, or modify indexes.

20
01:06:54,000 --> 01:07:00,000
Alembic tracks these changes in versioned migration files.
Each migration can be applied or rolled back.

21
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:06,000
First, initialize Alembic with the init command.
alembic init migrations

22
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:12,000
This creates a migrations directory with configuration files.
It also creates a versions directory where our migration scripts will live.

23
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:18,000
Now edit alembic.ini in the project root.
Find the sqlalchemy.url line.

24
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:24,000
You can leave the placeholder value.
We will override the database URL in env.py instead.

25
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:30,000
This is safer because it keeps credentials out of version control.
The actual URL will come from our settings at runtime.

26
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:36,000
Now replace the entire migrations/env.py file with our custom version.

27
01:07:36,000 --> 01:07:42,000
Let me explain what this env.py does.
It configures Alembic to run migrations in two modes. Offline and online.

28
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:48,000
Offline mode generates SQL scripts without connecting to a database.
Online mode connects directly and applies migrations.

29
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:54,000
Notice that target_metadata is set to None.
We will update this later when we have our ORM models.

30
01:07:54,000 --> 01:08:00,000
The run_migrations_offline function gets the database URL from the config.
It configures Alembic to generate SQL without a live connection.

31
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:06,000
The run_migrations_online function creates an engine from the config.
It connects to the database and runs migrations directly.

32
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:12,000
Finally, we check if Alembic is in offline mode.
If yes, run offline. If no, run online.

33
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:18,000
Now let's create our first migration script.
This will establish the baseline schema.

34
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:24,000
Create a file in migrations/versions called 001_initial_migration.py

35
01:08:24,000 --> 01:08:30,000
The revision ID is 001.
down_revision is None because this is the first migration.

36
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:36,000
The upgrade function adds the PostgreSQL extensions we need.
Vector for embeddings, uuid-ossp for UUID generation.

37
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:42,000
Also pg_trgm for trigram text search.
And btree_gin for advanced indexing.

38
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:48,000
These are the same extensions we enabled in Docker's init script.
We include them here for Alembic to track.

39
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:54,000
The downgrade function is empty.
Dropping extensions is risky, so we leave it as a no-op.

40
01:08:54,000 --> 01:09:00,000
Notice that this migration does NOT create the tables.
Our tables were already created by the Docker init script.

41
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:06,000
But future migrations will use Alembic's create_table operations.
This ensures all schema changes are versioned and repeatable.

42
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:12,000
Why does upgrade only create extensions?
The filings, financial_chunks, and analysis_history tables were created by the Docker init script in Phase 1.

43
01:09:12,000 --> 01:09:18,000
Alembic's job going forward is to track schema changes.
Migration 001 is the baseline that says everything up to this point already exists.

44
01:09:18,000 --> 01:09:24,000
Future migrations add columns, create indexes, or modify tables.
They go in 002, 003, and so on.

45
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:30,000
Now apply the migration.
alembic upgrade head

46
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:36,000
Verify with alembic current.
Output should show 001 followed by head in parentheses.

47
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:42,000
Alembic is now ready to track all future schema changes.



[## [SECTION: Step 10 — Token Counter & Chunker (Components #16–17)]]

48
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:48,000
Now let's build our text processor for chunking.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/processing/text_processor.py

49
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:54,000
This converts ParsedFiling objects into FinancialChunk ORM instances.
Ready for vector embedding and database storage.

50
01:09:54,000 --> 01:10:00,000
Let me explain two key design decisions before we write code.

51
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:06,000
First, why tiktoken instead of estimating with len divided by 4?
The divide by 4 estimate is wrong in every edge case that matters.

52
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:12,000
Short words, numbers, financial abbreviations, and non-ASCII text
all tokenise differently. tiktoken gives you exact token counts.

53
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:18,000
It uses the same BPE tokeniser as the actual model.
So chunk boundaries are precise, not estimates.

54
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:24,000
Second, why section-aware chunking?
A naive chunker splits at 512 tokens regardless of content structure.

55
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:30,000
This puts the end of MD&A and the start of Risk Factors in the same chunk.
That confuses the retriever.

56
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:36,000
Section-aware chunking guarantees a chunk never spans two different sections.
Each chunk belongs to exactly one section.

57
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:42,000
Now let's import our dependencies.
We need logging, uuid, and dataclasses.

58
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:48,000
We import tiktoken for token counting.
From our application, we import get_settings and FinancialChunk.

59
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:54,000
And from utils, we import ChunkingError.
We also use TYPE_CHECKING for conditional imports.

60
01:10:54,000 --> 01:11:00,000
First, define a ChunkSpec dataclass.
This is a specification for how a single chunk should be created.

61
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:06,000
It contains the text, section name, chunk index, token count,
filing ID, ticker, filing type, fiscal year, and optional metrics.

62
01:11:06,000 --> 01:11:12,000
Now the TextProcessor class.
In __init__, we load settings and get the tiktoken encoding.

63
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:18,000
We use the cl100k_base encoding.
This covers GPT-4 and the text-embedding-3 series.

64
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:24,000
We store chunk size and overlap from settings.
If tiktoken fails to load, we raise ChunkingError.

65
01:11:24,000 --> 01:11:30,000
Now the process method.
This is the public entry point for chunking a parsed filing.

66
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:36,000
First, we check if the parsed filing has any sections.
If not, we raise ChunkingError.

67
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:42,000
Then we iterate through each section.
If a section has no text, we skip it.

68
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:48,000
For each section, we call _chunk_section.
This returns a list of chunks for that section.

69
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:54,000
We extend the overall chunk list and update the global index.
Finally, we log how many sections became how many chunks.

70
01:11:54,000 --> 01:12:00,000
Two utility methods.
count_tokens returns the exact token count for a string.

71
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:06,000
estimate_cost calculates the OpenAI embedding cost for a list of chunks.
It returns total tokens and estimated cost in US dollars.

72
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:12,000
This is useful for understanding your embedding budget.
For text-embedding-3-large, the cost is about 13 cents per million tokens.

73
01:12:12,000 --> 01:12:18,000
Now the internal _chunk_section method.
This splits a single section's text into overlapping token-bounded chunks.

74
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:24,000
First, we tokenise the full section text using tiktoken.
If there are no tokens, we return an empty list.

75
01:12:24,000 --> 01:12:30,000
If the entire section fits in one chunk,
we return a single chunk with all the text.

76
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:36,000
Otherwise, we use a sliding window.
We set a start pointer and move it forward by chunk size minus overlap.

77
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:42,000
For each window, we take tokens from start to end.
We decode them back to text using tiktoken's decode method.

78
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:48,000
If the decoded text is very short, less than 50 characters,
we skip it and break out of the loop.

79
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:54,000
We build a chunk for each window and increment the chunk index.
We advance the start pointer by the step size.

80
01:12:54,000 --> 01:13:00,000
If step size is zero or negative, we log a warning and break.
This prevents infinite loops if overlap is set incorrectly.

81
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:06,000
Finally, _build_chunk constructs a FinancialChunk ORM instance.

82
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:12,000
We instantiate a TextParser to extract metrics from the chunk text.
Note that this happens on every call, which is fine for a tutorial.

83
01:13:12,000 --> 01:13:18,000
In production, you would inject the TextParser once in __init__.
But for clarity in a course, we keep it explicit.

84
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:24,000
We call extract_metrics on the chunk text.
This returns a dictionary of financial metrics.

85
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:30,000
Then we create a FinancialChunk with all the fields.
Note that embedding is set to an empty list.

86
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:36,000
The embedding will be populated later by the embeddings module.
This separation of concerns keeps each module focused.

87
01:13:36,000 --> 01:13:42,000
Now let's update the processing package __init__.py.
We import TextProcessor from text_processor.
Then expose it in __all__.

88
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:48,000
Now anywhere in the application, you can import.
from financial_rag.processing import TextProcessor

89
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:54,000
Our text processor is complete.



[## [SECTION: Step 11 — Embedding Client (Components #18–21)]]

90
01:13:54,000 --> 01:14:00,000
Now let's build our embeddings module.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/retrieval/embeddings.py

91
01:14:00,000 --> 01:14:06,000
This is a dual-provider embedding client.
OpenAI for production, sentence-transformers for development.

92
01:14:06,000 --> 01:14:12,000
Before we write code, let me explain a critical issue.
The dimension mismatch problem.

93
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:18,000
Your SQL schema has vector with 3072 dimensions.
That's for OpenAI's text-embedding-3-large model.

94
01:14:18,000 --> 01:14:24,000
But your development settings default to all-MiniLM-L6-v2.
That model produces only 384-dimensional vectors.

95
01:14:24,000 --> 01:14:30,000
You cannot insert a 384-dim vector into a 3072-dim column.
PostgreSQL will reject it with a dimension mismatch error.

96
01:14:30,000 --> 01:14:36,000
For local development, change your .env file.
Set EMBEDDING_PROVIDER to local, and EMBEDDING_DIMENSIONS to 384.

97
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:42,000
For production with OpenAI, use provider openai,
model text-embedding-3-large, and dimensions 3072.

98
01:14:42,000 --> 01:14:48,000
Now let's understand the design of this module.

99
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:54,000
First, imports. We need logging and time.
From tenacity, we import retry, retry_if_exception_type, stop_after_attempt, and wait_exponential.

100
01:14:54,000 --> 01:15:00,000
From our application, we import get_settings.
From utils, we import EmbeddingError.

101
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:06,000
We also define cost per million tokens for OpenAI models.
text-embedding-3-large costs 13 cents per million tokens.

102
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:12,000
Now define the EmbeddingProvider abstract base class.
This defines the protocol that all providers must follow.

103
01:15:12,000 --> 01:15:18,000
Each provider must have a dimensions property,
and both sync and async embed_batch methods.

104
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:24,000
Now the OpenAIEmbeddingProvider.
This uses text-embedding-3-large and requires an API key.

105
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:30,000
In __init__, we check if the API key exists.
If not, we raise EmbeddingError with a helpful message.

106
01:15:30,000 --> 01:15:36,000
We create both sync and async OpenAI clients.
The sync client is for bulk ingestion, the async client for real-time queries.

107
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:42,000
Notice the retry decorator on embed_batch.
It retries only on EmbeddingError, up to 3 attempts.

108
01:15:42,000 --> 01:15:48,000
It uses exponential backoff. wait 2 seconds, then 4, then up to 30 seconds.
This handles rate limits gracefully.

109
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:54,000
Inside the method, we call the OpenAI embeddings API.
We pass the model, input texts, and requested dimensions.

110
01:15:54,000 --> 01:16:00,000
We track latency and token usage.
We also calculate the cost of the request.

111
01:16:00,000 --> 01:16:06,000
Then we validate that the returned dimensions match what we expected.
If not, we raise EmbeddingError.

112
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:12,000
The async version uses the async OpenAI client.
The structure is identical but uses await.

113
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:18,000
Both methods have the same retry decorator and error handling.
This ensures consistency across sync and async usage.

114
01:16:18,000 --> 01:16:24,000
Now the LocalEmbeddingProvider.
This uses sentence-transformers with no API key required.

115
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:30,000
In __init__, we import SentenceTransformer inside the method.
This prevents import errors if the package isn't installed.

116
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:36,000
We load the model by name from settings.
This may take a moment on first run as it downloads the model.

117
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:42,000
The embed_batch method encodes texts using the local model.
We use convert_to_numpy equals True for performance.

118
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:48,000
Then we convert each numpy array to a Python list.
This ensures we return plain lists, not numpy arrays.

119
01:16:48,000 --> 01:16:54,000
The async version runs the sync method in an executor.
This prevents blocking the async event loop.

120
01:16:54,000 --> 01:17:00,000
Now the EmbeddingClient class.
This is the public interface that the rest of the application uses.

121
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:06,000
In __init__, we load settings and call _build_provider.
The provider is selected based on EMBEDDING_PROVIDER.

122
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:12,000
_build_provider has auto-fallback logic.
If OpenAI is requested but no API key exists, we fall back to local.

123
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:18,000
But only in development or testing environments.
In production, missing API key raises an error.

124
01:17:18,000 --> 01:17:24,000
The embed_texts method handles batching automatically.
It splits the input texts into batches of EMBEDDING_BATCH_SIZE.

125
01:17:24,000 --> 01:17:30,000
For each batch, it calls the provider's async embed method.
Then it extends the results list.

126
01:17:30,000 --> 01:17:36,000
This is where the actual HTTP calls happen.
Batching is critical for efficiency with OpenAI.

127
01:17:36,000 --> 01:17:42,000
The embed_chunks method takes a list of FinancialChunk objects.
It extracts the chunk_text from each chunk.

128
01:17:42,000 --> 01:17:48,000
It calls embed_texts to get all embeddings.
Then it populates each chunk's embedding field in place.

129
01:17:48,000 --> 01:17:54,000
This method is the primary interface for the ingestion pipeline.
You pass your chunks, and it returns them with embeddings.

130
01:17:54,000 --> 01:18:00,000
Finally, embed_query is a convenience wrapper.
It embeds a single query string for similarity search.

131
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:06,000
Now let's update the retrieval package __init__.py.
We import EmbeddingClient from embeddings.
Then expose it in __all__.

132
01:18:06,000 --> 01:18:12,000
Now anywhere in the application, you can import.
from financial_rag.retrieval import EmbeddingClient

133
01:18:12,000 --> 01:18:18,000
Our embeddings module is complete.
Now you can turn text chunks into vectors.



[## [SECTION: Step 12 — Chunks Repository (Component #23)]]

134
01:18:18,000 --> 01:18:24,000
Now let's build the chunks repository.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/chunks.py

135
01:18:24,000 --> 01:18:30,000
This is the core RAG retrieval table.
It owns vector similarity search for the entire application.

136
01:18:30,000 --> 01:18:36,000
The chunks repository has three critical operations.
Similarity search, MMR search, and bulk upsert.

137
01:18:36,000 --> 01:18:42,000
First, imports. We need logging and UUID.
From pgvector.sqlalchemy, we import Vector.

138
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:48,000
From SQLAlchemy, we import Float, Integer, SmallInteger, String, Text, func, select, and text.
And the JSONB and UUID types from postgresql dialects.

139
01:18:48,000 --> 01:18:54,000
From our application, we import Base from database,
BaseRepository from base, and our custom exceptions.

140
01:18:54,000 --> 01:19:00,000
Now define the FinancialChunk ORM model.
This maps to the financial_chunks table we created in Phase one.

141
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:06,000
We have id as primary key, filing_id as foreign key,
and denormalised fields like ticker, filing type, and fiscal year.

142
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:12,000
Denormalisation means we store these values directly in the chunks table.
This avoids expensive joins on every similarity search.

143
01:19:12,000 --> 01:19:18,000
The embedding column uses pgvector's Vector type.
Notice it's set to 384 dimensions for local development.

144
01:19:18,000 --> 01:19:24,000
We also have metrics and entities as JSONB columns.
These store extracted financial data and named entities.

145
01:19:24,000 --> 01:19:30,000
And a sentiment score from minus one to plus one.
Finally, model_version tracks which embedding model produced this vector.

146
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:36,000
Now the ChunksRepository class.
It inherits from BaseRepository with FinancialChunk as the model.

147
01:19:36,000 --> 01:19:42,000
We set model_class equal to FinancialChunk.
Then let's add the similarity search method.

148
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:48,000
First, similarity_search. This finds the most semantically similar chunks.
It uses cosine distance, the standard metric for embeddings.

149
01:19:48,000 --> 01:19:54,000
Let me explain the ef_search parameter.
HNSW stands for Hierarchical Navigable Small World.

150
01:19:54,000 --> 01:20:00,000
It's the index type pgvector uses for approximate nearest neighbour search.
ef_search controls the recall versus speed trade-off.

151
01:20:00,000 --> 01:20:06,000
Higher ef_search, like 200, searches more graph nodes.
This gives better recall but is slower.

152
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:12,000
Lower ef_search, like 40, is faster but may miss true nearest neighbours.
The default 100 is a good balance for financial text.

153
01:20:12,000 --> 01:20:18,000
Notice we use SET LOCAL to scope the setting to the current transaction.
It resets automatically when the session closes.

154
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:24,000
We use the cosine_distance operator on the embedding column.
This returns distance, where zero means identical and two means opposite.

155
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:30,000
We convert distance to similarity with one minus distance.
Then we add metadata filters for ticker, filing type, fiscal year, and section.

156
01:20:30,000 --> 01:20:36,000
We order by distance ascending and limit the results.
The method returns a list of chunks with their similarity scores.

157
01:20:36,000 --> 01:20:42,000
Now the MMR search method.
MMR stands for Maximal Marginal Relevance.

158
01:20:42,000 --> 01:20:48,000
Standard similarity search can return ten near-duplicate chunks.
All from the same paragraph, just repeating the same information.

159
01:20:48,000 --> 01:20:54,000
MMR solves this by balancing two things.
Relevance to the query and diversity among the results.

160
01:20:54,000 --> 01:21:00,000
The formula is. lambda times similarity, minus one minus lambda times redundancy.
Lambda of 1.0 means pure similarity, zero means maximum diversity.

161
01:21:00,000 --> 01:21:06,000
First, we fetch fetch_k candidates by similarity search.
Typically 20 candidates for every 5 results returned.

162
01:21:06,000 --> 01:21:12,000
Then we iteratively select the candidate that maximizes the MMR score.
We remove selected candidates from the remaining list.

163
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:18,000
The result is a diverse set of chunks that still match the query.
This is much better for RAG than pure similarity search.

164
01:21:18,000 --> 01:21:24,000
Now bulk_upsert. This inserts or updates chunks in bulk.
Upsert means update if exists, insert if not.

165
01:21:24,000 --> 01:21:30,000
We use PostgreSQL's INSERT with ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE.
This makes re-ingestion safe.

166
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:36,000
If a chunk with the same ID already exists, we update its text, embedding, and metadata.
If not, we insert a new row.

167
01:21:36,000 --> 01:21:42,000
This is critical for idempotent ingestion pipelines.
You can run the same ingestion twice without creating duplicates.

168
01:21:42,000 --> 01:21:48,000
Two more utility methods.
get_by_filing returns all chunks for a filing, ordered by chunk index.

169
01:21:48,000 --> 01:21:54,000
count_by_ticker returns the total chunk count for a ticker.
This is useful for monitoring and analytics.

170
01:21:54,000 --> 01:22:00,000
Finally, a static method _cosine_similarity.
This computes cosine similarity between two vectors in pure Python.

171
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:06,000
Note that this is only used during MMR candidate re-ranking.
It is not on the hot path for similarity search.

172
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:12,000
The actual similarity search uses pgvector's native operator.
That is much faster because it runs inside PostgreSQL.

322
01:37:06,000 --> 01:37:12,000
Now let's update the processing package __init__.py file.

324
01:37:18,000 --> 01:37:24,000
We import TextProcessor from text_processor.
Then we expose it in __all__.

325
01:37:24,000 --> 01:37:30,000
Now anywhere in our code, we can simply write.
from financial_rag.processing import TextProcessor

326
01:37:30,000 --> 01:37:36,000
The processing package is complete.
Text chunking is now available to the rest of the application.



[## [SECTION: Step 13 — Vector Store (storage/vector_store.py)]]

173
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:18,000
Now let's build the vector store orchestrator.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/storage/vector_store.py

174
01:22:18,000 --> 01:22:24,000
This sits between the processing layer and the retrieval layer.
It orchestrates the full chunk to embed to store pipeline.

175
01:22:24,000 --> 01:22:30,000
The vector store has three main responsibilities.
Embedding chunks, upserting into PostgreSQL, and registering filings.

176
01:22:30,000 --> 01:22:36,000
First, imports. We need logging and TYPE_CHECKING.
From retrieval, we import EmbeddingClient.

177
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:42,000
From storage, we import get_db_client.
And from repositories, we import ChunksRepository, FilingsRepository, and Filing.

178
01:22:42,000 --> 01:22:48,000
Now the VectorStore class.
In __init__, we create an EmbeddingClient instance.

179
01:22:48,000 --> 01:22:54,000
We log which provider is being used and the embedding dimensions.
This helps with debugging configuration issues.

180
01:22:54,000 --> 01:23:00,000
The ingest method is the full pipeline for a single filing.
It takes chunks, filing metadata, and a file hash.

181
01:23:00,000 --> 01:23:06,000
It returns a tuple of filing ID and the number of chunks stored.
Let me walk through each step.

182
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:12,000
Step one. deduplication check.
We create a database session and instantiate FilingsRepository.

183
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:18,000
We check if a filing with this hash already exists.
If yes, we raise DuplicateFilingError.

184
01:23:18,000 --> 01:23:24,000
This prevents ingesting the same filing twice.
The ingestion pipeline is idempotent.

185
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:30,000
Step two. embed all chunks.
We call embed_chunks on the embedding client.

186
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:36,000
This method takes a list of FinancialChunk objects.
It populates the embedding field on each one.

187
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:42,000
The embedding client handles batching automatically.
It also tracks token usage and cost.

188
01:23:42,000 --> 01:23:48,000
Step three. register the filing.
We generate a new UUID for the filing ID.

189
01:23:48,000 --> 01:23:54,000
We create a Filing ORM instance with all the metadata.
Ticker, filing type, fiscal year, source URL, and file hash.

190
01:23:54,000 --> 01:24:00,000
We set ingested_by to VectorStore and is_active to True.
Then we add it to the database using FilingsRepository.

191
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:06,000
Step four. bulk upsert the chunks.
First, we set the filing_id on all chunks.

192
01:24:06,000 --> 01:24:12,000
They had placeholder IDs from the text processor.
Now we attach them to the correct filing.

193
01:24:12,000 --> 01:24:18,000
Then we call bulk_upsert on ChunksRepository.
This inserts or updates all chunks in a single operation.

194
01:24:18,000 --> 01:24:24,000
We log the completion with filing ID and chunk count.
Then return both to the caller.

195
01:24:24,000 --> 01:24:30,000
Now the stats method.
This returns storage statistics for monitoring.

196
01:24:30,000 --> 01:24:36,000
We get counts for chunks and filings.
Optionally filtered by a specific ticker.

197
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:42,000
We also include the embedding provider and dimensions.
This helps track which model is powering your vectors.

198
01:24:42,000 --> 01:24:48,000
The stats method will be called by the API routes.
It gives you visibility into your vector store size.

199
01:24:48,000 --> 01:24:54,000
Our vector store is complete.
Now you can ingest filings and search them with natural language.



[## [SECTION: Step 14 — Cache Namespace Constant]]

200
01:24:54,000 --> 01:25:00,000
Now let's add the cache namespace constant for queries.
Open src/financial_rag/storage/cache.py

201
01:25:00,000 --> 01:25:06,000
We already have namespace constants for chunks, embeddings, and analysis.
Now we need NS_QUERY for document retrieval results.

202
01:25:06,000 --> 01:25:12,000
Add this constant just after the build_key function.
NS_QUERY equals query.

203
01:25:12,000 --> 01:25:18,000
This will be used by the document retriever to scope cache keys.
All query results will be stored under finrag colon query colon namespace.

204
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:24,000
The cache client is now ready for the document retriever.

341
01:39:00,000 --> 01:39:06,000
Now let's update the storage package __init__.py to include NS_QUERY.

342
01:39:06,000 --> 01:39:12,000
We already have namespace constants from the cache module.
NS_CHUNKS, NS_EMBEDDINGS, NS_ANALYSIS, NS_MARKET.

343
01:39:12,000 --> 01:39:18,000
Now we add NS_QUERY to the imports.
And add it to __all__.

344
01:39:18,000 --> 01:39:24,000
This constant is used by the document retriever for cache keys.
All query results will be stored under finrag colon query namespace.

345
01:39:24,000 --> 01:39:30,000
The storage package now exports all namespace constants.
Other parts of the application can access them easily.



[## [SECTION: Step 15 — Document Retriever & Hybrid Search (Components #24–28)]]

205
01:25:24,000 --> 01:25:30,000
Now let's build the document retriever.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/retrieval/document_retriever.py

206
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:36,000
This retrieves relevant chunks for a query using vector similarity search.
It adds a Redis cache layer on top of VectorStore.

207
01:25:36,000 --> 01:25:42,000
Why caching? Repeated queries with the same question and filters
hit the database and embedding API on every request.

208
01:25:42,000 --> 01:25:48,000
That's expensive and slow.
Caching returns results instantly without recomputing.

209
01:25:48,000 --> 01:25:54,000
First, imports. We need hashlib, json, logging, and dataclasses.
From config, we import get_settings.

210
01:25:54,000 --> 01:26:00,000
From storage.cache, we import NS_QUERY, build_key, and get_cache_client.
From storage.vector_store, we import VectorStore.

211
01:26:00,000 --> 01:26:06,000
And from utils, we import RetrievalError.

212
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:12,000
Now define the RetrievalResult dataclass.
This represents a single retrieved chunk with its similarity score.

213
01:26:12,000 --> 01:26:18,000
It contains chunk ID, text, ticker, filing type, fiscal year,
section name, similarity score, and extracted metrics.

214
01:26:18,000 --> 01:26:24,000
The to_context_string method formats this result for the LLM prompt.
It includes a source header so the model can cite its sources.

215
01:26:24,000 --> 01:26:30,000
For example. source AAPL 10-K FY2023, Risk Factors, score zero point nine two.
Then the chunk text.

216
01:26:30,000 --> 01:26:36,000
The from_chunk class method converts a FinancialChunk ORM object
into a RetrievalResult with its similarity score.

217
01:26:36,000 --> 01:26:42,000
Now the DocumentRetriever class.
In __init__, we load settings and optionally accept a VectorStore instance.

218
01:26:42,000 --> 01:26:48,000
If no vector store is provided, we create one.
This allows dependency injection for testing.

219
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:54,000
The retrieve method is the main public API.
It takes a question and optional filters.

220
01:26:54,000 --> 01:27:00,000
We determine the effective limit and score threshold.
Limit defaults to TOP_K_RESULTS from settings.

221
01:27:00,000 --> 01:27:06,000
Score threshold defaults to VECTOR_SEARCH_THRESHOLD.
Chunks below this score are filtered out.

222
01:27:06,000 --> 01:27:12,000
First, we check the cache.
If use_cache is True, we build a cache key from all query parameters.

223
01:27:12,000 --> 01:27:18,000
The cache key is a SHA-256 hash of the question and filters.
We scope it under the NS_QUERY namespace.

224
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:24,000
If we find a cached result, we return it immediately.
This bypasses the vector search entirely.

225
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:30,000
If not cached, we call search on the vector store.
We pass the question and all filters.

226
01:27:30,000 --> 01:27:36,000
The vector store handles embedding and similarity search.
It returns raw results with similarity scores.

227
01:27:36,000 --> 01:27:42,000
We convert each raw result to a RetrievalResult.
We filter out any chunks below the score threshold.

228
01:27:42,000 --> 01:27:48,000
Then we cache the results for future queries.
We only cache if we have results and caching is enabled.

229
01:27:48,000 --> 01:27:54,000
The cache TTL comes from settings.
Default is one hour.

230
01:27:54,000 --> 01:28:00,000
Now the build_context method.
This assembles retrieved chunks into a single context string for the LLM.

231
01:28:00,000 --> 01:28:06,000
It respects a token budget to avoid exceeding the model's context window.
Budget defaults to MAX_CONTEXT_TOKENS from settings.

232
01:28:06,000 --> 01:28:12,000
We use tiktoken again to count tokens exactly.
We iterate through results in order of relevance.

233
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:18,000
For each result, we call to_context_string to get a formatted block.
We encode it and count the tokens.

234
01:28:18,000 --> 01:28:24,000
If adding this block would exceed the budget, we stop.
We log how many tokens and chunks were used.

235
01:28:24,000 --> 01:28:30,000
Then we join all blocks with a separator of two newlines and dashes.
This creates a clear separation between sources.

236
01:28:30,000 --> 01:28:36,000
Now the cache helper methods.
_build_cache_key creates a deterministic key from query parameters.

237
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:42,000
We put all parameters into a dictionary and serialize to JSON.
We sort keys to ensure the same parameters produce the same string.

238
01:28:42,000 --> 01:28:48,000
Then we take a SHA-256 hash of that string.
This gives us a fixed-length, unique identifier.

239
01:28:48,000 --> 01:28:54,000
We use build_key with NS_QUERY to namespace the key.
Final format. finrag colon query colon the hash.

240
01:28:54,000 --> 01:29:00,000
_get_cached retrieves from Redis and deserializes.
If Redis fails, we log a warning and return None.

241
01:29:00,000 --> 01:29:06,000
Cache failures are non-fatal.
We fall back to vector search instead of crashing.

242
01:29:06,000 --> 01:29:12,000
_set_cached serializes results and stores them in Redis.
We convert each RetrievalResult to a dictionary first.

243
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:18,000
Then we call client.set with the key and serializable data.
The TTL is handled automatically by the cache client.

244
01:29:18,000 --> 01:29:24,000
Now let's build the hybrid search module.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/retrieval/hybrid_search.py

245
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:30,000
Hybrid search combines vector similarity with full-text search.
It uses Reciprocal Rank Fusion, or RRF, to combine scores.

246
01:29:30,000 --> 01:29:36,000
Why do we need this? Vector search alone works well for semantic questions.
But it can struggle with exact terms like ticker symbols or dollar amounts.

247
01:29:36,000 --> 01:29:42,000
Full-text search excels at exact matches.
Hybrid search gives you the best of both worlds.

248
01:29:42,000 --> 01:29:48,000
First, imports. We need logging and TYPE_CHECKING.
From sqlalchemy, we import text for raw SQL queries.

249
01:29:48,000 --> 01:29:54,000
From our application, we import get_settings.
From retrieval, we import RetrievalResult and EmbeddingClient.

250
01:29:54,000 --> 01:30:00,000
From storage, we import get_db_client and ChunksRepository.
And from utils, we import RetrievalError.

251
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:06,000
Now the HybridSearcher class.
In __init__, we load settings and create an embedding client.

252
01:30:06,000 --> 01:30:12,000
We also define the RRF constant K.
60 is the standard value from the original 2009 paper.

253
01:30:12,000 --> 01:30:18,000
The search method is the public entry point.
It takes a question and optional filters.

254
01:30:18,000 --> 01:30:24,000
We determine the effective limit and alpha weight.
Alpha defaults to HYBRID_SEARCH_ALPHA from settings, which is 0.7.

255
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:30,000
We fetch three times the requested limit for candidates.
Fusion will narrow the list down.

256
01:30:30,000 --> 01:30:36,000
Then we run both searches concurrently using asyncio.gather.
Vector search and text search happen in parallel.

257
01:30:36,000 --> 01:30:42,000
After both searches complete, we fuse the results using RRF.
The fused results are sorted by combined score.

258
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:48,000
The _vector_search method embeds the question.
Then it calls similarity_search on the chunks repository.

259
01:30:48,000 --> 01:30:54,000
This returns a list of chunks with cosine similarity scores.
The scores range from 0 to 1, where 1 is identical.

260
01:30:54,000 --> 01:31:00,000
The _text_search method uses PostgreSQL's trigram similarity.
It requires the idx_chunks_text_trgm GIN index we created in Phase one.

261
01:31:00,000 --> 01:31:06,000
We build a parameterized SQL query with similarity function.
The similarity function compares chunk_text to the query string.

262
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:12,000
We apply the same metadata filters as vector search.
Ticker, filing type, and fiscal year.

263
01:31:12,000 --> 01:31:18,000
We order by trigram similarity descending.
And limit to the requested number.

264
01:31:18,000 --> 01:31:24,000
If the text search fails, we log a warning and return an empty list.
Text search failures are non-fatal.

265
01:31:24,000 --> 01:31:30,000
After getting matching IDs and scores, we fetch the full chunk objects.
Then we return them as a list of chunk and score tuples.

266
01:31:30,000 --> 01:31:36,000
Now the most important method. _reciprocal_rank_fusion.
This combines the two ranked lists into one.

267
01:31:36,000 --> 01:31:42,000
Let me explain RRF.
Reciprocal Rank Fusion combines two ranked lists without needing raw scores.

268
01:31:42,000 --> 01:31:48,000
Vector similarity and trigram similarity are not on the same scale.
Vector scores cluster around 0.7 to 0.9.
Text scores cluster around 0.1 to 0.4.

269
01:31:48,000 --> 01:31:54,000
You cannot average them directly. RRF solves this by using rank position.
It cares about where a document appears in each list, not the raw score.

270
01:31:54,000 --> 01:32:00,000
The formula is. alpha times one over K plus vector rank,
plus one minus alpha times one over K plus text rank.

271
01:32:00,000 --> 01:32:06,000
K is 60, the standard RRF constant.
Alpha is the weight for vector results, default 0.7.

272
01:32:06,000 --> 01:32:12,000
Documents that appear in both lists get contributions from both terms.
They receive a higher fused score.

273
01:32:12,000 --> 01:32:18,000
Documents that appear in only one list still get a partial score.
They are included but ranked lower.

274
01:32:18,000 --> 01:32:24,000
First, we build rank maps for both result sets.
Rank is one-indexed, meaning the first result has rank 1.

275
01:32:24,000 --> 01:32:30,000
We collect all unique chunk IDs across both lists.
Then we build a lookup dictionary from ID to chunk object.

276
01:32:30,000 --> 01:32:36,000
For each chunk ID, we compute the vector RRF contribution.
If the chunk is in the vector list, we add one over K plus its rank.

277
01:32:36,000 --> 01:32:42,000
If not, we add zero.
Same for text RRF.

278
01:32:42,000 --> 01:32:48,000
Then we compute the fused score as alpha times vector RRF
plus one minus alpha times text RRF.

279
01:32:48,000 --> 01:32:54,000
We sort by fused score descending and take the top limit.
Then we convert each to a RetrievalResult and return.

280
01:32:54,000 --> 01:33:00,000
Now let's update the retrieval package __init__.py.
We import DocumentRetriever, RetrievalResult, HybridSearcher, EmbeddingClient.
And from query_engine we import QueryEngine and QueryResult.

281
01:33:00,000 --> 01:33:06,000
Then we expose all six in __all__.
Now any part of the application can import from financial_rag.retrieval.

282
01:33:06,000 --> 01:33:12,000
Let me summarize when to use hybrid search.

283
01:33:12,000 --> 01:33:18,000
Use hybrid search as a fallback when vector search confidence is low.
When the best vector score is below VECTOR_SEARCH_THRESHOLD.

284
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:24,000
Also use it when the query contains specific financial terms.
Ticker symbols, dollar amounts, dates, or product names.

285
01:33:24,000 --> 01:33:30,000
The hybrid search module is complete.
You now have three retrieval options. vector, MMR, and hybrid.



[## [SECTION: Common Errors and Fixes — Phases 2 & 3]]

286
01:33:30,000 --> 01:33:36,000
Let me walk through common errors in Phases 2 and 3.
And how to fix them.

287
01:33:36,000 --> 01:33:42,000
Error one. tiktoken loading fails.
cl100k_base encoding not available.

288
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:48,000
The cause is an outdated tiktoken version.
Or network issues downloading the encoding.

289
01:33:48,000 --> 01:33:54,000
The fix. upgrade tiktoken with pip install.
pip install dash upgrade tiktoken.

290
01:33:54,000 --> 01:34:00,000
Error two. dimension mismatch on insert.
384-dim vector into 3072-dim column.

291
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:06,000
The cause is using local embeddings but production schema.
Set EMBEDDING_DIMENSIONS to 384 in your .env file.

292
01:34:06,000 --> 01:34:12,000
Or change the schema to vector of 384.
But better to keep schema as 3072 and configure .env correctly.

293
01:34:12,000 --> 01:34:18,000
Error three. Chunk overlap validation fails.
CHUNK_OVERLAP_TOKENS must be less than CHUNK_SIZE_TOKENS.

294
01:34:18,000 --> 01:34:24,000
The cause is .env file has overlap greater than or equal to chunk size.
Reduce CHUNK_OVERLAP_TOKENS to 50 or 100.

295
01:34:24,000 --> 01:34:30,000
Error four. OpenAI API key missing in production.
EmbeddingError at runtime.

296
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:36,000
The cause is EMBEDDING_PROVIDER set to openai but no key.
The fix. set OPENAI_API_KEY in .env or switch to local provider.

297
01:34:36,000 --> 01:34:42,000
Error five. sentence-transformers not installed.
LocalEmbeddingProvider import error.

298
01:34:42,000 --> 01:34:48,000
The cause is missing package.
Run pip install sentence-transformers.

299
01:34:48,000 --> 01:34:54,000
Error six. pgvector operator not found.
cosine_distance operator doesn't exist.

300
01:34:54,000 --> 01:35:00,000
The cause is pgvector extension not created in database.
Run CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector in psql.

301
01:35:00,000 --> 01:35:06,000
Then recreate your containers with docker compose down minus v and up minus d.

302
01:35:06,000 --> 01:35:12,000
Error seven. SQLAlchemy async engine not connected.
DatabaseClient._engine is None.

303
01:35:12,000 --> 01:35:18,000
The cause is calling get_db_client without calling connect first.
Call await db.connect() at application startup.

304
01:35:18,000 --> 01:35:24,000
Error eight. HNSW ef_search parameter not applied.
SET LOCAL hnsw.ef_search fails.

305
01:35:24,000 --> 01:35:30,000
The cause is using pgvector version older than 0.5.0.
Upgrade pgvector in your Docker image.

306
01:35:30,000 --> 01:35:36,000
Bookmark this section.
When you hit an error, you'll know exactly where to look.



